review: I loved reading this book--such an interesting follow-up to Severance for me. What if the apocalypse was kind of whimsical? Because I am a glutton forI loved reading this book--such an interesting follow-up to Severance for me. What if the apocalypse was kind of whimsical? Because I am a glutton for punishment, I was a bit more intrigued by the events of the actual pandemic than the post-apocalyptic world, but the mixed-up timelines kept me thoroughly gripped throughout... Beautiful writing, I was especially struck by the sparing use of grief--I wrote off the lack of grief as kind of an oversight until a death towards the end that illustrated the numbness of mass grief/survival versus individual grief. review: Definitely one of my favorites of the summer, but in a certain Male Manipulator kind of way. Interconnected stories about overeducated millennials feeDefinitely one of my favorites of the summer, but in a certain Male Manipulator kind of way. Interconnected stories about overeducated millennials feeling lost and pretentious and old, which isn't exactly where I am now but definitely could be soon. Honestly lots of the characters could be interchangeable, but the real success for me was capturing emotions and traits that are so real but not usually portrayed so vividly--the idea that one character doesn't really have strong opinions on things, or the super visceral feeling of losing your car keys and feeling yourself go kind of crazy because of it. "Bad Feelings" was my favorite, just because the thoughts going through that guy's head were so familiar to me. If it sounds boring it's because it kind of... is, but in a way that really hit on something for me....more

review: Had this recommended to me years ago and finally got to it — so glad I did. There’s a lot you can read into this book, and it made me realize mainstreHad this recommended to me years ago and finally got to it — so glad I did. There’s a lot you can read into this book, and it made me realize mainstream gender conversations have come a long way since even 2019. Is this speculative, or is it all just metaphor? I kind of chose to read into the latter. But beyond the sex/magic of the whole concept, I was mostly just blown away by the subtlety of Paul’s interior life — like, as a reader, I could tell when Paul wasn’t that into someone before he even could, and I think the whole thing with Diane was such a good depiction of infatuation with a person who ultimately just doesn’t match up. Meanwhile the repetition of “Tony Pinto” and then is he emergence of Robin at the end showed me a whole different way of looking at a person. Favorite main character in a while, really fun to read but also wrenching. Want to loan this to lots of people!!...more

review: Going on my all-time-favorites list for sure, and can't believe it took me this long to get around to it. George Saunders is a master of juxtapositionGoing on my all-time-favorites list for sure, and can't believe it took me this long to get around to it. George Saunders is a master of juxtaposition (comedy and tragedy, humanistic and absurd, etc) and this is a master work. The balance between truth and fiction was perfectly struck and perfectly confusing. Definitely found this book super Ulyssean--it's an obvious influence, but 166 speakers rather than three made the speaker notes super warranted, and helped ground me in the weirdness of it all. I read an interview with him where he said he's never trying to make a "point," he's just telling a story and it often gets to a point--that really stuck with me, because his stuff always ends of making me cry. For this one it was richard bevins iii and the versions of all the characters that could have been but never were. Wow. I would kill to be able to write like this so can hopefully do less than kill and get a little bit closer....more

review: Really, really excellent. One of my new favorites. I dissolved into these characters and this universe and got happily lost in every beautifully-spun Really, really excellent. One of my new favorites. I dissolved into these characters and this universe and got happily lost in every beautifully-spun tangent. One of the most interesting elements of this novel for me was the way that incredibly important events (with a few very notable exceptions) were just dropped offhand in large blocks of other movement or thought--with the history and themes being covered, I would have expected large portions devoted to certain deaths, marriages, etc, but often a critical detail was just sprinkled in, somehow making the whole thing feel at once more grandiose and more intimate. We got to live in the details and the tangents, and those made up the big shifts, and when those shifts happened offscreen, they were simply alluded to. Really interesting tactic... Overall, immersive and beautiful! Made me feel things and escape for a bit. ...more

author: Eugenides, Jeffrey

review: I really couldn't tell how self-aware this book was, and that made it rather hard to take seriously. As a recent liberal arts graduate, I enjoyed the I really couldn't tell how self-aware this book was, and that made it rather hard to take seriously. As a recent liberal arts graduate, I enjoyed the pretentious obsessions with semiotics and Derrida, although it seemed unrealistic that more characters didn't get punched in the face for being so annoying. As for the love triangle--it was hard for me to know if the characters were supposed to be as despicable as I found them. While each was compellingly constructed, it was hard to move past the fact that both Leonard and Mitchell both literally assaulted women and/or children and that wasn't really accounted for much in their character at all. It just wasn't really clear what, if anything, Eugenides is saying about this group of people or these particular characters, but maybe that's the whole point? I got through this book quickly and was pretty drawn into the story (I think Leonard's section was the most interesting), but it was definitely my least favorite Jeffrey Eugenides book--Middlesex is one of my all-time favorites....more
